{
  "text": "In addition and consequently, results from the current study reinforce the concept that although regulation of gene expression at the mRNA level (i.e., transcription and RNA stability) is an important contributor to heterogeneity among spermatogonia, regulation of message use (i.e., translational control) can also contribute to this heterogeneity, and both of these mechanisms appear to be operating in developing male germ cells [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Thus, although mRNA was detected for the differentiation markers, Stra8 and Kit, in all and nearly all Id4-eGFP \u00fe spermatogonia, respectively, the corresponding proteins were detected in only a small fraction of Id4-eGFP \u00fe cells by immunofluorescence. Indeed, KIT and STRA8 proteins were only localized to spermatogonia with dim eGFP epifluorescence, but because the half-life of eGFP is estimated to be .26 h [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] , it is possible that eGFP \u00fe cells that are also KIT \u00fe or STRA8 \u00fe had transitioned out of an SSC state to become progenitor spermatogonia. Although a lack of available technology to interrogate protein expression in single cells has limited complementary protein studies to the extent to which mRNA levels can now be interrogated [CITATION_5] , new technologies, such as mass cytometry, are emerging that may allow parallel quantitative examination of .10 individual proteins within individual cells [CITATION_6] . It is also possible that differences in microRNA (miRNA) expression may contribute to the disparities we observed between mRNA and protein levels for certain gene products, and future studies could use existing strategies to catalog mature miRNA heterogeneity among individual spermatogonia [CITATION_7] . Thus, a comprehensive understanding of the molecular differences that distinguish subpopulations of male germ cells clearly requires consideration of the transcriptome (mRNA and miRNA) and proteome in each case.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "22660309",
    "[CITATION_2]": "205360370",
    "[CITATION_3]": "27910789",
